				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=88797&amp;sid=e58df94d8a8ec250475f6cfa673e4d73"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				It IS worth buying right now.  It adds a great deal of game mechanics and graphical quality to the Shogun/Medieval Total War packages. 
<br />

<br />
On the strategic level, movement distances of marching your armies are more realistic than in the predecessors.  Proximity of ports, resources, cities, etc. definitely matter more than just being next door to a province.  The map is beautiful.  The game turns on strategic level are 6 months and weather is a factor in winter.  Ships cannot travel infinite distance per game turn as in the previous versions.  They have limits.  Land forms, such as mountains and rivers, are very significant factors in planning army movement.
<br />

<br />
On the battlefield level, the soldiers are now actuall 3D objects, not sprites.  The unit AI is more realistic - morale, target fixation, movement momentum, etc. all make a bigger difference when you start flinging cavalry units around the map.
<br />

<br />
The biggest challenge for most people will be in maintaining a large enough family.  Your faction is run by the members of your family -- individual male family members are needed because they are better city administrators as well as better generals.  You can have a city run by a generic governor, but it will probably not make as much money or maintain as high a degree of satisfied citizens as a decent family member acting as governer.  Likewise, you may have a decent cohort captain leading an army comeptently, but he won't do as well in a battle as a skilled general from the family.
<br />

<br />
At the same time, you have to deal with the fact that you are competing for resources, territory, and prestige with two other Roman families who are ostensibly your allies but you know someday, they will turn on you.  To top it off, the Senate keeps asking you to do things for them that have definitely military, economic, and political ramifications.  Doing them makes the senate happy, failing to do them pisses the senate off -- and sometimes, doing them can be hazardous to your situation relative to other countries and factions out there.
<br />

<br />
As for the learning curve, the tutorial and in-game help really do a lot for you and make it much more painless to deal with.  Creative Assembly really broke new ground when they made Shogun:Total War and Medieval was a huge step upward.  Rome is orders of magnitude above in both complexity and realism.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
