			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I'll write a full review when I get home from work.  For now:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">1. Is it worth buying right away?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, I think so.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">3. Learning Curve is steep to have you playing more than a few hours, and not just a person that can micro good can be good at the game?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
I would say the learning curve is simple to moderate.  If you have some grasp of how military units of that era worked, I would say simple.  If not, moderate.  The strategic part of the game is fairly simple.  Its basicaly Civilization II, without quite as much stuff.  If you build a trader in your city, it starts trading with no need for input from you.  If you build a port, it starts sea trading without input from you.  
<br />

<br />
The biggest part of the learning curve are the Real Time battles, and learning what units work well against what.  I'd say that R:TW has the most realistic combat of the 3 TW games so far.  If you understand that charging light cavalry into a a phalanx'ed group of spearmen is bad, and that leaving an archer unit exposed to a cavalry charge is bad, then you understand.  There are also some other little things, like if the enemy has an 8-star faction heir leading and army, and you have a 1-star captain, its going to be really hard to win the fight no matter what.  
<br />

<br />
Once you figure out what kills what best and if you have a grasp of basic military tactics (flanking, skirmishing, how to use missile units), then you wont have any trouble in the real time section of the game.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Is it the same at medieval/viking invasion? Or are there new aspects to it? Besides venue.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Similar, but enough new stuff that make it very much worth buying.  With each new TW game, Creative Assembly has added to and refined their engine and game.  The things that needed to get better got better.  The things no one liked went away.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
