		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=88846&amp;sid=e58df94d8a8ec250475f6cfa673e4d73#88846"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Fri Oct 08, 2004 9:15 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Rome: Total War</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=88846&amp;sid=e58df94d8a8ec250475f6cfa673e4d73"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Okay, here is my long review, along with some strategy notes that I've discovered over the first 20-30 turns (I haven't played deep into a game yet, I've started over several times since I've been experimenting).  The real time battles section is longest, so if you feel you have a good grasp of this, skip it.
<br />

<br />
First the campaign map.  Graphics are very good.  Only thing I don't like about it is that I tend to lose my agents (usually diplomats) if I don't keep careful track of where they are.  If I have one big complaint, its that the overview map doesn't have enough color differences and it can be a pain to tell who's in control of what.  
<br />

<br />
Things I liked.
<br />

<br />
Trade routes.  They are obvious and easy to recognize.  Basically, you'll see little caravans one your roads.  The more caravans there are, the more trade you're producing.  For ports, you'll see trade lanes going from one port to another so you know who you're trading with.  This was a huge improvement over M:TW.
<br />

<br />
Diplomacy is also much better.  For those that played M:TW those diplomats, princesses and spys were pretty useless as there seemed to be (at least to me) very little rhyme or reason for the computers diplomatic actions.  There was also no penalty for breaking treaties, the computer would happily offer you a cease-fire then attack you again the next turn.  Diplomats have a MUCH larger range of actions now.  Spys are quite helpful and dont die nearly as much.  Assassins are great.  Don't leave home without them.  If I have room, I keep 3 or 4 assassins with each large army I have and if I run into a high quality computer general I just assassinate him (not always successful, even with 4 assassins, but if you get him, it can turn a hard battle into a bone crushing victory).
<br />

<br />
Instead of having an army "everywhere" in a province at once, an army actually moves around inside a province.  Provinces have terrain, and terrain is a big deal.  If your army is standing on a bridge and you get attacked, you'll get an easy bridge defense.  Same with mountain passes, forests, and deserts.  Two or three good heavy infantry units with archer support can hold a bridge against a horde of gaul.  
<br />

<br />
Building units.  They cost money, like M:TW, but they also cost population now.  Very realistic.  If you want a city to grow fast, you cant build much military there, as it draws from the population.  Because city improvements rely partly on city size, you cant churn out military units if you ever want to get to the best building upgrades.  This also effects you tax income.  If you draw population out of a city by turning population into troops, you decrease your tax base, so you're paying more than just the build cost for a unit.
<br />

<br />
Economy, growth, happyness.  All easily seen on the city planning screen.  Shows your growth rate, happyness and income for the city.  Also shows EVERYTHING that effects these numbers.  For example, you may be gaining happyness from garrison (80%), govornor (30%), buildings (20%) and (other @#%$) (30%) for a 160% happyness.  Happyness is lowered by squalor (20%) and high tax rate (20%), so your overall happyness for that city is 120% (need this number to stay above 100%).  These are just example numbers, but the game very clearly breaks down whats going on, why its going how it is, and what you can do to fix it (if you have advice turned on).
<br />

<br />
------------------------------------------------------
<br />

<br />
Real Time Battles
<br />

<br />
I'm very impressed with the improvements to the AI!  It is so much better than M:TW.  Gone are the days where the computer would casually stroll up to your line-of-battle while letting you hammer it with your missile units.  The AI has a good grasp of tactics, and when to do what.  If they outnumber you, they'll try to flank you.  If they have a lot of missile units, they'll attempt to stand off and shoot you.  It also seems to me the computer has a good idea of what units are good against what.  You will rarely see it do stupid @#%$ like charge cavalry into a group of spearmen in the woods (which it was notorious for in M:TW).  If you have any knowledge of military tactics of this era, you'll still have an advantage, but not nearly as much as in M:TW.  The AI is no longer a push-over.
<br />

<br />
Morale.  This is even more important than in M:TW.  In fact they introduce specific, morale breaking units (war dogs, incidiary pigs, elephants) designed specifically to be "throw away" units that deplete enemy moral.  Archers can light their arrows on fire.  They kill less troops this way, but cause a much bigger morale penalty to the enemy.
<br />

<br />
Battles are a little more line-of-battle oriented, especially against "civilized" enemies.  If you outnumber the enemy, use cheap units to hold his battle line while you flank with cavalry.  Cavalry charges are MUCH MUCH more devestating in R:TW!!!!!  I can't stress this enough.  In fact, a cavalry charge can cause a unit to route even before the cavalry engage them, especially if its a flank or rear charge.  Cavalry units will totally decimate light infantry or missile units.  They'll simply charge right through them, kill everything in their path, then turn around and charge again.  Heavy cavalry have a much better line breaking ability in wedge formation than they did in M:TW.  Watch out for this, the computer WILL do it.  You'll wonder why his cavalry are charging your heavy infantry only to see them cut a big hole in your line and have his secondary troops pour through the gaps.  Cavalry rule the battlefield.  They are your shock troops.  If the enemy has cavalry, and you don't, you're in big, big trouble.  
<br />

<br />
Heavy and light infantry are effective against spear units, however they will still take some initial losses before they get in close.  Spear/pike units are devestating to cavalry (unless you flank them).  Lots of light infantry units have (very limited) missile weapons (javalins or pila).  DO NOT let roman units throw pila at you!!!!  If you're playing the romans, try to use Pila if you can.  They're hard to time, and since the computer wont just stand there and let you throw missile weapons at it like in M:TW, you'll have to figure out the timing (and sometimes its just not possible).  
<br />

<br />
Lots of units have special abilities.  Learn them.   
<br />

<br />
In the early turns, the Roman units are better than just about anything else.  One-to-one they are better than their enemy equals (roman light infantry are better than gual light infantry, and so forth).  With equal leaders, expect about a 3 or 4 to 1 kill ratio.  Non-roman units, especially barbarians types (guals, germans, etc) tend to have larger units.  Early roman light infantry (Hastarii) are 81 men at full strength.  Early gual light infantry (war band) are 121 men at full strength.  I would have no concerns about a Hastarii unit unit defeating a war band handily assuming there were no outstanding conditions.  
<br />

<br />
Fatigues is also a big factor.  Dont let tired units keep fighting if you have a choice.  They are much more prone to routing, and as I said, routing snowballs a lost faster in R:TW.  Us this to your advantage.  Concentrate on routing one or two enemy units in a line-of-battle.  Of course, you dont want to do that if it means exposing your own flanks.  When all your (or the enemy) units route, its over.  If you route the computer, you get the option of ending the fight or continuing the battle.  If you have cav, continue the battle and run down and kill everything you can.  Especially guals.  Their units are cheap and big and there will be a LOT of them.  A whole lot.  The more you kill, the more you dont have to fight next year.
<br />

<br />
@#%$ gauls.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
